<PageMeta category="Understand the model" variant="brand" updated="Draft · Updated 2026-06-14" />

  <h1>Identity &amp; classification</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    Two decisions carry more weight than any other in the model. The <strong>identity crux</strong>
    (<a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0005">ODR-0005</a>) answers the question PDTF JSON cannot:
    <em>what is the rigid, identity-bearing "property"</em> when the source schema has no first-class
    property object at all? The <strong>classification doctrine</strong>
    (<a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0027">ODR-0027</a>) answers how every <em>type</em> in the model is
    assigned: by coded set-membership, not by a subclass tree.
  </p>

  <nav class="callout callout--note" aria-label="On this page">
    <p class="callout__label">On this page</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#crux">The implicit-Property crux</a> — the three-class split (ODR-0005)</li>
      <li><a href="#uprn">UPRN is a contingent Quality</a> — never the IC, never owl:sameAs</li>
      <li><a href="#hard-cases">The named hard cases</a> — how Property identity behaves</li>
      <li><a href="#doctrine">Classification doctrine</a> — facets, not subclass trees (ODR-0027)</li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <h2 id="crux">The implicit-Property crux (ODR-0005)</h2>
  <p>
    PDTF JSON has no first-class "property" object, yet an RDF consumer needs a rigid, identity-bearing
    subject to attach everything to. ODR-0005 (Council session-005; Queen Guarino) splits the conflated
    notion into <strong>three UFO Substance Kinds</strong>, each committed to a DOLCE Endurant, each with
    its <em>own</em> identity criterion — not one conflated entity:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Class</th><th>UFO / DOLCE</th><th>Identity criterion</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>opda:Property</code></td>
        <td>Substance Kind / PhysicalObject</td>
        <td>spatial-material continuity, with a legal-record discontinuity override</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>opda:LegalEstate</code></td>
        <td>Substance Kind / NonPhysicalEndurant</td>
        <td>rights-bundle persistence (survives transfer, charges, easements) — <strong>may be unregistered</strong> at common law</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>opda:RegisteredTitle</code></td>
        <td>Substance Kind (informational) / NonPhysicalEndurant</td>
        <td>title-number lineage + registry-event history; carries a distinct published-personal-data PII regime under the HMLR open register</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The split is what gives the <strong>unregistered-house-before-first-registration</strong> case a coherent
    answer (a <code>LegalEstate</code> with no <code>RegisteredTitle</code>), and gives <code>RegisteredTitle</code>
    instances a class-level discriminator for ICO Subject Access processing. The three are joined by co-reference —
    the controlled <code>opda:identifiesSameProperty</code> predicate and SHACL key-matching —
    <strong>never <code>owl:sameAs</code></strong>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="uprn">UPRN is a contingent Quality — never the IC, never <code>owl:sameAs</code></h2>
  <p>
    <strong>UPRN is a contingent <em>Quality</em> of a <code>opda:Property</code>, never the identity
    criterion, and never asserted with <code>owl:sameAs</code></strong> (the <code>owl:sameAs</code>-across-UPRN
    option was rejected <em>unanimously</em> at session-005). A property can change UPRN — administrative
    re-numbering is captured by a reified <code>opda:UPRNSuccessionEvent</code> under
    <code>prov:wasDerivedFrom</code>, materialised into the validation report by a SHACL-AF rule at
    <code>sh:Info</code> severity, and the Property's identity <em>persists</em> through it. Two records sharing
    a UPRN are <strong>not</strong> thereby the same legal estate. Forbidden anti-patterns:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>owl:sameAs</code> between any two UPRN-bearing nodes — propagates every context's properties onto every other, irreversibly under inference.</li>
    <li>Treating UPRN <em>or</em> address as the identity criterion — both are administratively contingent (UPRN) or a mode of presentation (address).</li>
    <li>Keying a Role — a Role borrows identity from its bearer and never supplies its own (ODR-0005 anti-pattern §3).</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="muted">
    Worked exemplars exercise exactly these surfaces: <code>flat-with-split-uprn</code>,
    <code>flat-no-uprn-newly-converted</code>, <code>rural-plot-inspire-no-uprn</code>,
    <code>unregistered-pre-first-registration-house</code> — see <a href="/ontology/exemplars">Exemplars</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="hard-cases">The named hard cases (how <code>opda:Property</code> identity behaves)</h2>
  <p>
    Per ODR-0001's per-<code>kind:&nbsp;pattern</code> discipline, each identity criterion is exercised over
    <strong>five named hard cases</strong> rather than asserted abstractly. For <code>opda:Property</code>:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Hard case</th><th>Disposition</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {HARD_CASES.map(([c, d]) => (
        <tr><td><strong>{c}</strong></td><td>{d}</td></tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The unifying rule: <strong>physical-material continuity governs, with a legal-record discontinuity
    override</strong>. <code>opda:LegalEstate</code> and <code>opda:RegisteredTitle</code> each carry their own
    five-hard-case walk in ODR-0005 §3b/§3c.
  </p>

  <h2 id="doctrine">Classification doctrine — facets, not subclass trees (ODR-0027)</h2>
  <p>
    ODR-0027 adopts wholesale the sibling corpus's decade-stable
    <strong>classification-over-inheritance</strong> doctrine, grounded in ISO 25964 faceted classification,
    W3C SKOS, FIBO, and OntoClean/UFO. The doctrine is six rules:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>What it says</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {DOCTRINE.map(([r, d]) => (
        <tr><td><strong>{r}</strong></td><td>{d}</td></tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The OntoClean cascade behind R1 (ODR-0011 §8a): <em>anti-rigid → never a subclass</em>;
    <em>+R∧−I → classify (coded)</em>; <em>+R∧+I∧+D → Relator</em>; <em>+R∧+I∧−D → subclass</em>. The net effect:
    the ~{40} OWL classes are kept deliberately few and rigid, while the <strong>47 SKOS concept schemes</strong>
    carry all the varying classification — see <a href="/ontology/vocabularies">Vocabularies (SKOS)</a>.
  </p>

